issue.title: Add a module for Flutter

labels.name: 🌱 good first issue
labels.description: Good first issue to get your feet wet.

issue.body:
## Feature Request

#### Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.
No, I haven't really had an issue, but I'm new to Starship and it really bothered me that Starship doesn't display the Flutter version in a Flutter project. It does recognize Dart, and when people code in Dart it's almost always for Flutter.

I saw that #609 was closed without implementing Flutter support, but I'm not sure about the reason.

#### Describe the solution you'd like
Starship should show the Flutter version as a module, like `[🇫 v3.3.7]`. Because Flutter doesn't have its own file extension, we can read each .dart file in a directory to check if `package:flutter/material.dart` or `cupertino.dart` is imported, and display the module if such an import statement is found.

It would be nice to make the module compatible with [FVM](https://fvm.app) too.

#### Describe alternatives you've considered
None

issue.title: Intl lookup can't work without code generation
issue.body:
Hello,

I wanted to have decentralized traductions instead of having them transformed/generated to dart. But I find myself totally blocked by the intl API and way of doing things. 

Take this example: `String complex(String name, String name2) => Intl.message('$name2 love $name', args: [name, name2], name: 'complex');`

In ARB format it will be generated like this:
```
"complex": "{name2} love {name}",
"@complex": {
  "type": "text",
  "placeholders": {
    "name": {},
    "name2": {}
  }
},
```

To be able to find translations Intl is using `MessageLookup ` under the hood, so I was trying to extends it and make my own lookup based on ARB I have downloaded. 

For that we need to implement this method:
```
String? lookupMessage(String? messageText, String? locale, String? name, List<Object>? args, String? meaning, {MessageIfAbsent? ifAbsent}) {
```

So here I'll receive the sentence `"{name2} love {name}",` and now I'm blocked, because I have a list of `args` but no way to find which one is `name` and which one is `name2`.

I there any workaround or other way I can achieve this ?

issue.title: Database is locked after hot restart and sometimes in production
issue.body:
I am using a single instance of my database with `VmDatabase` as executor.

When the app starts , data is loaded from remote and inserted into the database in several transactions.
If I hot restart the app during this time, there is a chance, that the database is locked after the restart.

This would be ok if it was only happening during development but I am seeing the same stacktraces in Sentry from production users, very rarely but it happens. I am not sure how that can happen.

I have a similar problem with Sembast using `sqflite_ffi` (https://github.com/tekartik/sembast_sqflite/issues/5)  which seems to have been solved by not using the ffi implementation.

Since both use `sqlite3`, I wonder if it is related or if you have any idea what could prevent this.

pull_request.title: Always clear carry buffer on new image start
pull_request.body:
This change clears the carry whenever a new SOI is detected. We tested it in production for ~3 months and crashes due to image decoding issues have gone down >80% according to Firebase Crashlytics.

Depending on network connectivity, a camera might send an incomplete image. Displaying this results in a gray flicker, since the image cannot be properly decoded. This library "solves" this problem already by only sending the image off for rendering when an EOI sequence is detected.

However, wen an SOI sequence is detected after a broken image, the carry is not reset. This leads to "half of a broken image and a proper image" being sent to the Flutter `Image` tag together, which sometimes (depending on where the data cuts off) crashes it in Flutter < 3.2.

Even with the change in Flutter 3.2 that keeps the app from crashing in this case, I still think this is helpful to prevent future regressions.

EDIT: This was originally inspired by the issue described in https://github.com/mylisabox/flutter_mjpeg/issues/18

issue.title: Save mjpeg stream to disk?
issue.body:
Is it possible to save the data received in the stream to disk? 
Then I could add the "record video" feature to the app.

I see a new [frame pre-processor](https://github.com/mylisabox/flutter_mjpeg/commit/bdf07b309a94f749b105d26b09c2ada956df2e17) was just added to the Widget constructor but that is not yet released and I'm not 100% sure how to use that to write the mjpeg to disk.

pull_request.title: Always clear carry buffer on new image start
pull_request.body:
This change clears the carry whenever a new SOI is detected. We tested it in production for ~3 months and crashes due to image decoding issues have gone down >80% according to Firebase Crashlytics.

Depending on network connectivity, a camera might send an incomplete image. Displaying this results in a gray flicker, since the image cannot be properly decoded. This library "solves" this problem already by only sending the image off for rendering when an EOI sequence is detected.

However, wen an SOI sequence is detected after a broken image, the carry is not reset. This leads to "half of a broken image and a proper image" being sent to the Flutter `Image` tag together, which sometimes (depending on where the data cuts off) crashes it in Flutter < 3.2.

Even with the change in Flutter 3.2 that keeps the app from crashing in this case, I still think this is helpful to prevent future regressions.

EDIT: This was originally inspired by the issue described in https://github.com/mylisabox/flutter_mjpeg/issues/18

},

```

pull_request.title: Always clear carry buffer on new image start
pull_request.body:
This change clears the carry whenever a new SOI is detected. We tested it in production for ~3 months and crashes due to image decoding issues have gone down >80% according to Firebase Crashlytics.

Depending on network connectivity, a camera might send an incomplete image. Displaying this results in a gray flicker, since the image cannot be properly decoded. This library "solves" this problem already by only sending the image off for rendering when an EOI sequence is detected.

However, wen an SOI sequence is detected after a broken image, the carry is not reset. This leads to "half of a broken image and a proper image" being sent to the Flutter `Image` tag together, which sometimes (depending on where the data cuts off) crashes it in Flutter < 3.2.

Even with the change in Flutter 3.2 that keeps the app from crashing in this case, I still think this is helpful to prevent future regressions.

EDIT: This was originally inspired by the issue described in https://github.com/mylisabox/flutter_mjpeg/issues/18
